    ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯                                      ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
@{FG Shine}Welcome to @{B}AmiChannel News@{UB}@{FG Text}

Hello and welcome to the 11th issue of @{B}AmiChannel News@{UB}.

First  of  all,  I  would like to apologize for the delay of the release of this
issue.  I  wanted to release it on May, 24th, but because of the recent moves at
Amiga  (all  of  them positive), I was not able to edit the magazine. Anyway, it
is very likely that future issues will appear at the very end of the month.

So much things to speak about and so little space in this editorial. Let's start
with  Jim  Collas.  If  you have read these editorials, you probably know by now
that  I have criticized Amiga a lot in the Jeff's times. But things have changed
a  lot.  It's  true  that  there are not new products yet, but things are moving
faster and faster.

I  think  Jeff  Schindler knows what to do, but Jim Collas knows how to do these
things  happen  and not to spoil the weak hopes of the Amiga community. Amiga is
opening new ways of communication, hiring people with experience in the computer
industry,  and  releasing some drawing concepts for future Amiga projects ... In
short,  they  are in the right way for the success. Read more about this in this
issue.

The  first  Amiga  product  is not going to be a full computer, that's for sure.
Probably  we  are  going to see something like the CD32 in an A500 style, as the
first step  to  connect  all  the  electric  appliances  in  a house. And with a
transparent capability to access the Internet.

Just  imagine. I want to read the news from the Yahoo website. But I am 70 years
old  without  any  experience  with  computers.  Or  even  I  have  some  visual
deficiencies  (this  is for you johnnie :)). I use a wireless LCD tablet or even
pressing  a  key,  this  powerful multimedia computer (or information appliance)
connects  to  Yahoo  and instead of reading the news from an screen, I hear them
because the speech capability of the computer.

Sometimes (or very often), we forgot blind people. The current Amiga was able to
speak  from the very beginning, but it is not able to use this capability to the
full,  so blind people need to do tricks to read the Internet or even electronic
magazines.  We,  the  editors  of electronic magazines, need to pay attention to
them in order to make easy the reading of our mags.

If Amiga is going to succeed, it needs to speak from the very beginning. Support
for  blind  people  is  necessary.  The  competence  is  doing  it. Microsoft is
developing  special versions of Windows for blind people. As Amiga is developing
a full operating environment for home devices, this support is a must.

Remember to visit the @{B}SAUG-news @{UB}website, which is located in:

         @{B}www.saug.com/eng/selec.html@{UB}

or you can visit its mirrors located in:

         @{B}www.geocities.com/SiliconValley/Sector/2282/sau/index.html@{UB}

And if you want to contribute to this effort, you can send your articles to:

         @{I}angel@saug.org @{UI}

Thanks for reading and I hope you enjoy this issue.

===============================================================================
