@node not27 "POWER COMPUTING NEW DEVELOPMENTS"

@{U}@{B}POWER COMPUTING @{UB}NEW DEVELOPMENTS@{UU}

From: @{I}"Ben Vost" @{UI}@{I}<ben.vost@futurenet.co.uk>@{UI}

Just  got  news  from @{B}Power Computing @{UB}about a new board they'll have in the next
couple of days. Check it out and remember you heard it here first!

---

@{B}A4000 PowerFlyer @{UB}/ End of Budda Meditation! :)))

  * The  first @{B}Amiga 3000/4000 @{UB}EIDE/ATAPI controller supporting PIO-3, and PIO-4
    modes (16.6MB/sec)
  * Enhanced EIDE/ATAPI controller for @{B}ZORRO III @{UB}bus @{B}Amiga@{UB}s
  * Allow several times faster transfer than any @{B}ZORRO II @{UB}IDE/ATAPI controller
  * Two buffered and terminated IDE-Ports for up to four IDE-devices
  * Work independently from @{B}A4000 @{UB}standard IDE controller
  * Autoconfigurated @{B}ZORRO III @{UB}card
  * Very sophisticated software @{B}FastATA'99 @{UB}included.
  * Support HDD over 4GB
  * Autoboot from any removable media (@{B}Zip@{UB}, @{B}LS-120@{UB})
  * @{B}AllegroCDFS @{UB}- the fastest @{B}Amiga @{UB}CD filesystem included.

On  @{B}A4000 @{UB} two  devices  could be attached to standard IDE controller, next four
devices  to  @{B}A4000 @{UB}PowerFlyer. More than one @{B}A4000 PowerFlyer @{UB}could be installed
in  @{B}ZORRO  III @{UB} slots!  During  computer  start @{B}A4000 @{UB}could boot from any of HDD
attached to @{B}A4000 PowerFlyer @{UB}or from HDD attached to standard controller.

@{I}AllegroCDFS@{UI}

The fastest @{B}Amiga @{UB}CD filesystem!
The first @{B}Amiga @{UB}filesystem supporting UDF (format for Video DVD)!

  * Provides access to:
      * @{B}ISO 9660 @{UB}level 1, 2, 3
      * @{B}Joliet @{UB}(@{B}Win95/98 @{UB}long name) level 1, 2, 3
      * @{B}Rock Ridge @{UB}(with @{B}Amiga @{UB}Extensions)
      * @{B}CDDA@{UB}
      * @{B}UDF @{UB}(Video DVD)
  * @{B}Amiga @{UB}Protection bit supported
  * Built-in MultiSession support
  * Support SCSI and ATAPI devices (CD-ROM, CD-R, CD-RW, DVD)
  * Support for direct digitizing from standard audio CDs

---

Now,  obviously the DVD support is all well and good, but playing back video DVD
