@node not36 "FUSION OR SHAPESHIFTER?"

@{U}FUSION OR SHAPESHIFTER?@{UU}

In article <7gkpgd$6vi$1@news1epix.net> nospam@winbej.fakeisp.com (joe) writes:

> Any thoughts on the advantages and disadvantages to each?....joe

ShapeShifter is free now; there is no demo version of Fusion AFAIK. If you don't
have  a  GFX  card,  Fusion  has  faster  AGA  drivers, and OS8 (not 8.1 or 8.5)
reportedly  runs  better  on  Fusion,  though 8 is a waste, best to stick to the
freely  available  7.5.3 (/.5) or 7.6.1. I use a mix of 7.1 and 7.6.1, since 7.1
is the smallest and fastest of 68k MacOSes.

Others reported networking was easier with ShapeShifter, all I can say that I've
used  PPP  and  TCP/IP  over  Ethernet  in  both Classic and OT flavours without
problems  on ShapeShifter. Also, I tried MacLite 1200 some time ago and had some
filesystem trouble which Shapeshifter never had. On the other hand, I could only
format  a  SCSI  ZIP  with  major  trouble, and transfers to it would eventually
freeze  SS  (the Amiga side had no problems at all with the ZIP). This of course
could have been cybscsi.device, YMMV.

If  you  have  an  060, Fusion also should work better with some apps, or so I'm
told.  My system has trouble with some stuff, mainly M$ Word and MSIE (who would
have  thought..)  where  NS3.04  runs  fine. With some others SS, and especially
older  versions  (3.7)  work better. Also depending on the 68060.library you use
some  apps  work better with an older lib version (here some PhotoShop functions
and plugins crash with the latest libs).

ShapeShifter is now basically unsupported, except perhaps for some minor updates
which still might arrive, Fusion has a helpful and active mailinglist supporting
it,  or  so  I'm  told.  Fusion  PPC  however  is  basically  cancelled, whereas
ShapeShifter's author is working on various versions of Mac emulation which just
might make it to Amiga PPC in some form or the other.

Those  would be the major points I am aware of, the rest is up to you to try and
see what's best. There is no real speed difference between both emulations.
